At the end of the trade, the Prague stock exchange is in the negative
After the fall of Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with the ČEZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trade.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the trade, the Prague Stock Exchange returned with its fall the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in shares on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan of stabilization of the American financial sector, is also noticeable in our country.
Falling stock in Asia
The Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, even if the signs succeeded, during the day, in erasing some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange Hang Seng index lost four percent during trade, but later it erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the Chinese stock market movement in Hong Kong lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney stock market lost more than five percent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"The hesitation about the rescue action in the US will affect the financial markets around the world," observed Joseph Yam, the head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its own monetary policy, i.e. independent of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk that other countries would be affected.
The bloodbath of American actions
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the financial system support project, to which it should have devoted up to $700 billion (nearly 12 billion Kč).
Legislators thus renegotiate the call for support of President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should address the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. actions experienced a bloodbath and the major evidence of actions experienced the greatest fall in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, with a fall of such magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress gives way: US government can inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush agreed on a broader form of the financial assistance agreement to the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote at the beginning of next week.
U.S. legislators made a turning point in the talks on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of financial assistance of $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner) granted to the U.S. financial system.
Success is not certain, however.
Before the final version of the Act can be published and put to the vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be reviewed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Says Sunday to Reuters Barney Frank, the chairman of the House's Banking and Financial Regulation Committee.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be adopted should be a major psychological factor in reinvigorating financial markets.
Given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market aid can be effective, it will follow a "disillusionment".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our differing views on the form the market stabilization package should take," democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg Agency.
According to her, the final vote could be taken as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislators met with US finance minister Henry Paulson, in order to give the government a final form.
It should buy back from financial corporations the unsoldable real estate assets that result in considerable losses to financial enterprises and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still have to continue this market recovery plan, but I think we are there," says Paulson.
A signal for Asian exchanges
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on the declining stock markets.
According to the Democratic Senator, do not escape Harry Reid, the legislators are making sure that Congress reaches a final agreement on Sunday.
They want to calm investors before the start of trade in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the Congress' decision could influence trade on Monday.
At the moment, however, it is impossible to specify with certainty when the two Chambers of the American Congress will proceed to the vote, or if the negotiations are not likely to be blocked, at the last moment, by a particular problem.
Legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
Nevertheless, there will be many amendments to the law.
The total amount allocated to the system shall be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But, if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the possibility to block the remaining amount by two steps: first, an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush hailed progress in negotiations
Although the President can veto this decision, the Congress has the opportunity to put it as a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the purchase of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said that Mr. Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartite effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Chair of the Senate Banking Committee Christopher Dodd, Chief Negotiator, said that legislators agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors against losses, the discount agreement, and the progress of the plan on the axis of time.
The new law also provides for the limitation of such golden parachutes for directors of the companies participating in the program and establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also provides assistance for real estate owners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new advances in the case of mortgages that it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of the debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological Aid
According to Patria Finance Chief Economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its realization will be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that we don't know what the mechanism and price of buying back problematic assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek said this week to the iHNed.cz server.
If the plan is adopted now, or at the beginning of next week, it is not, according to Marek, as important as that.
"It is much more important that the congressmen agree this week that they support this plan and that we dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at the moment," Marek stressed.
An extreme struggle: MP3 players against mobiles.
We'll advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
However, there are sufficient reasons to obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy a high-end expensive gramophone for the house to put on Maxim Turbulenc's new album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there's vinyl discs in your shelves packed together, with rock art, jazz or blues, you're probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during the journeys, that is, compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
There, too, there are categories depending on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan would have trouble supporting earphones purchased for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions that are, of course, unknown to most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
Alongside the primary functions, phone calls and texting, he is able to read music and movies, record them, he has a camera of varying quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if you take Smartphones and communicators into account, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without disadvantages.
The greater the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between two recharges.
And music reading is one of the most important energy gophs.
There are few mobiles that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the rudimentary ones) are significantly more performing.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you sometimes call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second refill for work - this being valid even for the most expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are capable of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing, after reloading.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobile phones.
As far as players are concerned, you don't need any software, except (iPod).
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create a media library themselves classified according to the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or then according to the user's judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In the choice of a concrete device, you are particularly interested in the life of the accumulator, the capacity of memory, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of ordering.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it that for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3s.
Practically all mobiles are capable of this today.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or the player is able to read.
Everyone gets to read the MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will just have this format.
It is one of the most common formats, and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play WMA format music.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of online music.
Simply visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding operator's web pages (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to obtain a musical motive.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and is limited in most cases to fast-made radio tubes.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, the Internet or even the wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always wear their mobiles on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just need to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you forgot your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you still have headphones on you or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use built-in speakers, which have virtually all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, you can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of an output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best telephones and the best equipped, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone can ensure the order of the rudimentary readers - who do not necessarily correspond to the less expensive (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command with that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or of a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mobile internet that is randomly connected, followed by a huge data transmission invoice.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models support in principle only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones even come out with 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an irivar.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 kroner.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose more specialized mobile-walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and thus the ease of the control is close to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went the most in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) higher, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the above mentioned brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in Chechnya is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, on many occasions, Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
ČTÚ (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the European Commission's latest steps in the area of roaming charges regulation, a paradoxical situation may occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of cheaper Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Chechnya remain so high, in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has stated on several occasions that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, is chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently no longer very lucky (in fact, now it would find only frequencies difficult).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable fall in prices, to which the traditional operators had to react.
However, even before the riots such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those heard today at home were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to earn more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let's add that behind Mobilking there is the financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, the U:fon in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
For example, in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers text messages in Britain at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity hit.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who operates this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work at home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone's spokesperson, in doubt: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Chechnya, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The Mobilking launch will instead take place in other countries in our area," said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the financial group Penta.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of customers company, has not, for a long time, hidden its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We very much want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl.
So the future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that perhaps we could accommodate the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for the moment, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific ones.
For the time being, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specific nature of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
She adds: "It is virtually impossible for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs its attention to the completion of requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our view, means the most input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in line with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profit.
What is the point of facilitating the arrival of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to agree to themselves as larrons at fairs. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also bears witness to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on ČTÚ during the creation of U:fon was exerted by T-Mobile.
This is demonstrated by the information available to the public from the ČTÚ web pages.
Today, the U:fon lends itself as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in Chechnya.
The latter belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, in the face of this problem, the latter adopted its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded at this time, as the offer of potential stakeholders has previously not presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the UOHS Department of External Relations in response to our question.
Such a statement would not surprise operators' representatives.
But on the part of an Office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one benefits from its position on the market, such a declaration is more than confusing.
All the more so as Kristián Chalupa adds: "Across the country, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile telephone services."
However, pressure for an honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices does not appear to be part of UOHS's interests.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and the tough fight of competition.
"The Office has not identified any signs of anticompetitive behaviour in this regard, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore none has a corresponding increased responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecommunications regulator," said Chaloupa in his statement.
One of the many points of disagreement is the interpretation of the dominant position on the market.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitutes, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts suggest another view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically monopoly over its network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without accepting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the UOHS that three mobile operators are proceeding visibly in a similar way.
However, complaints from many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Bringing responsibility back to the ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the ÚOHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Regrettably, the recently adopted new telecommunications law has not succeeded in extending ČTÚ's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of UOHS must know this very well, but their interests seem to be elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
However, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudo operators, many in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but the latter are only partially public.
In most cases, there are companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
For example, private mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company does before the operator is a classic company customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she obtains special price offers (and others).
What is problematic is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If this were to happen, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would examine and that could lead to a cessation of cooperation with the company in question," answered our question on this issue Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not reached the managers of mobile operators.
Particularly in the case of the three companies mentioned there may be thousands of customers.
An operator, however, does not rule against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies bring them non-negligible profits, and at the same time, as opposed to the real virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický states the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the way of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
That is precisely what should seem strange at ČTÚ.
In addition, another question arises in the UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to content itself with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable fall in the price of services.
In virtually all the countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators were sometimes trying harder, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - a market too small or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It was precisely at this level, however, that regulators in developed countries intervened, which defended not the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they eventually got the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies treat this issue in the same way as a hot potato that is disposed of by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than beneficial to them in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the punch.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our home, the Czech mobile market may be back on the move.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will hardly be able to remain unfettered in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Citizenship Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde Domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with chorus and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the anthem arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national singing as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to make sure that the two singers, as well as the choir, had a good diction, so that we could understand the words, which they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj played for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the Theatre of States) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse of Saveters), original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple became naturally an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
