Pragian public transport (MHD) will introduce the chip into their ticketing system on Wednesday
On Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be inscribed in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Prague Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, which, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, it is accessible to about 100 thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a coupon 30 days or 90 days (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have it recorded on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (the Transport Agency), located at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy coupons via internet on the Dopravní podnik web pages: www.dpp.cz.
Over four hundred people took advantage of the service during the morning.
Those who will start using the online store can permanently forget the counters in the subway stations, where they had to trample impatience in long queues to get paper tickets.
In fact, they will buy their coupon online and will be recorded on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"At these points of contact, there is a desk available to passengers with trained staff, who will help interested people with the purchase by internet and, in addition, will record the coupon they have bought on their card," says the spokesperson for the Martin Opatrný project.
Next to the libraries, it will also be possible to record the electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, remind the machines to compose the tickets and the passengers have perhaps already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today, the city has five, but by the end of the year, there should be eighty," said Opatrný.
An automatic will control the coupon instead of the driver
The automatics that will work from tomorrow, are easy to use.
Simply enter the Opencard smart card and the coupon previously purchased will register itself on the card.
The electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surroundings of the city.
