The Sudetens demanded a referendum in the USA
The Germans of the Sudeten asked in 1945 for Šumava to be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the South Bohemian).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some Sudeten German groups allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a preserved letter in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov in the letter ask the US President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come into German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, "People, to whom the fate of Šumava is dear."
Since the accession to Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, attitude without regard, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the Šumava protectorate for now and forever.
"We cannot believe, that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, that oppresses and destroys minorities and that in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter of a million inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would have only to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Germans of the Sudetenians of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to see that the question of their expulsion from the Republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some were waiting for the United States and Great Britain to gain some kind of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When he was captured by the English at the end of the war and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to him to learn Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
An emotional campaign will attack the drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
A way to characterize the emotional media campaign that the Ministry of Transport intends to launch on Wednesday.
Minister Aleš ňebíček's office believes that it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behaviour.
This 150 million-dollar campaign will appear on television, radio, cinema, the Internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers of fast driving and driving alcohol.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
Above all, it wants to reach the consciousness of young drivers, bikers, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
It also bears witness to the "bloody" slogan of the whole campaign:
You don't think - you pay!
The phrase "You don't think about it" is inscribed in capital letters on the registration plate.
Then, in a pool of blood, there is the phrase "You will pay".
Which must symbolize that you can pay for life a moment of inattention.
The spots will "haunt" viewers until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where images with drastic images of accident victims can be seen commonly.
It estimates that this will lead to a decrease in the accident rate and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The strategy of sugar and whip against drivers
"What works with drivers is the sugar and whip system.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time when they grill a red light.
The whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
The risks must be reminded of the drivers," said Martin Kořán, transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is how we need information campaigns in the press and, above all, negative publicity, says the psychologist.
In his view, the signs indicating the danger to drivers are already less effective.
"When a static panel warns against danger, it will probably soon merge with the environment and drivers will not notice," Kořán said.
