Rats also have sensations
A rat or a cockroach escapes from danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same way when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to have proof of it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, one can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or in general consciousness, we enter hard-to-practice terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it does death, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, so some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the Cortex lateral prefrontal (because of its participation in the short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the Cortex prefrontal, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from the other primates.
Another significant feature could be the linguistic nature of Man: much of his existence is related to language, which often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if the consciousness were not to depend on the language, it would surely influence it, so that the animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differentiate much from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured nor, because of this particular Hardware, to analyze based on our own experience, then its observation poses major problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
We could examine the processes of animal consciousness without considering their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, one focuses more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the importance of the Cortex prefrontal in the realization of visualization.
But what then results for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defence system located in the brain (or its sequences, like the reactions of the body) grabs living memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the cortex regions that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volubile nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that the sensations from primitive activities arise in the regions of the cortex body sensation and brain stem, as Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
As this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could quite participate in transversal sensations of any kind.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe that is undisputed.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in humans and rats is probably also felt as such in both cases: how, however, can one verify whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but what if he feels afraid?
In my view, similar behaviours are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Of course, the nerve comparison helps: rats and men have similar brain trunks, but cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem at the origin of the sensations?
And even if we could prove this for man: how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
