"I photograph the master outside the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no strapping.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in privacy, in these moments unknown to the general public, where one discovers with intimate gestures and the stolen looks of artists who do not care to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some stage performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the special iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programme of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and a unique character.
What interests me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of the flamenco stars. "
With the festival "Popular Song of Mines", Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, remind classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not the dance or the singing itself, but the personality and character of the artist who captivates the public with his art.
The search for the essentials and the magic was the constant of this work that is presented these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book of the portraits exhibited in the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph people's portraits, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a little while.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters you sometimes don't know or who only give you a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true. "
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at number 20 of the rue de la Mata (a street parallel to the People of Hercules) which will be opened until 16 October next.
