Some kids talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who speak during their sleep.
The first time this happens, it may surprise you, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a mild alteration of sleep called sleepyness.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one talking at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day after the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night sicknesses (to pee in bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stress or overexcited situations.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, murmurs or, on the contrary, with cries, tears, long speeches ...
In the event that somniloquia becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to obtain an explanation for this problem.
We said that it is a mild alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep impairment that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who are struggling to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm inside.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleepyos appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless since he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he talks, he sleeps and then rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or to check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not be tempted to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because by sleeping, he's not conscious so he can organize his mind.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so be careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can interview him at night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
