Before flying to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a detour through Brittany.
In the face of the demonstration of strength of the fishermen who strongly disturbed on Monday the access of several Breton and Norman ports, the President of the Republic decided to go Tuesday morning to the port of Guilvinec, in Finistère, to meet their representatives there.
They promised to welcome him "in a constructive spirit" and hope that he "will come with concrete proposals".
A presidential visit that falls at the same time as a general meeting of the "crisis committee" set up by the Breton fishermen to obtain measures in the face of the rising prices of diesel, which reached a record of more than €1.14 per litre on average.
According to the spokesman for Elysée David Martinon, the president "will discuss with them solutions that can be imagined to help their companies regain competitiveness and to secure the conditions of employment and remuneration of sailors".
