The Interview - Blood Back Safe
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Above all, he regained public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, in the face of this tragedy and public grumbling, the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to stop such a disaster from happening again.
While Justice Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, barely 38% of people still trusted the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
As a result of efforts to improve the safety of blood and work products in the field over the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before proudly asserting that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its inception, on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were occurring in Europe, says the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we did not know at all whether this disease could be transmitted by blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious disease may result, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
A few years ago, however, it has been shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode has shown us that the precautionary principle that has been applied makes sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique was introduced on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which directly detect the presence of the virus itself in donor blood and not antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
TANs have shortened the silent period, which extends from the time the person was infected to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This substantially reduced the risk that some donors would be infected without knowledge and could not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products annually, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I think we can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover our health," says the Chief Executive Officer of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continues before pointing out that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
"Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
As anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need to recharge red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which on average accounts for only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria can still give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a malaria-affected country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
As today's life is so frantic, one rarely finds time to spend an hour giving blood," desolates Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to collect more than a thousand per year.
We should start proposing transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Several moms are disappointed they can't have access to it," as Héma-Québec has no means of offering this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
