Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice-President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the Orwellian states that the world's largest gold company has filed a defamation suit of six million against three authors and a small, penless publishing house with the aim of launching a "transparent public debate".
While judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable money to prepare their defence and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by almost bottomless pockets of mining.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is, moreover, often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a settlement to the amicable that will stutter the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to address the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally conducted through the exchange of ideas rather than by batons.
Thus, it was sufficient for mining to open its books, records and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects from the back of his hand the petitions and letters of support for Black Canada's authors.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while disregarding the views of the same public?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to fat lawyers paid and not all Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports Black Canada's authors and publishers do so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a bailiff (in pursuit of the "public debate", Barrick Gold has, moreover, just filed a notice against Black Canada authors urging them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal speech, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to quote credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under duress of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by Black Canada authors.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss to the academic world, as well as to the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and Congress leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it provides for: better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default of payment, and a right to look at the salaries paid to the managers of the rescued enterprises.
The US Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," said the Democrat.
"This is the fundamental point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense," Republican Judd Gregg said.
The negotiations had turned to sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would cause on the mood of investors.
The cut-off time was the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, without failing to express their discontent at being forced to reach that end.
Senator Democrat Barack Obama attributed himself to the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that aimed at allowing homeowners to keep their homes, and that on the salary of managers of state-recovered companies.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
Asked on another channel to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines I have read [show] that this is something that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unsellable claims of US financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of mortgages at risk (subprime) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and leading to a freezing of liquidity and the debandade of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans who blew up the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed that they have come out of this impasse since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the corners for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added stipulating that if the government were to bear losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to which an additional 100 billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
Another 350 billion is expected to be endorsed by another Congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that will be worth dividends in the event of profit and that he will be able to resell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure procedures for housing units for real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on the remuneration and severance pay paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The plan's architects would like to see it put to the vote in the House of Representatives today, and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Indeed, votes continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
"Certainly, Washington does not hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of profiting from taxpayers".
Animator of a small group at the Congress called "the sceptics' caucus", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred prominent economics professors, including three Nobel Prize winners, wrote to us to tell us: Congress is asked not to rush and carefully examine the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, we once again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had given up acquiring its competitor in full sinking since it lost EUR 2 billion (US 2.9 billion) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, one recovers a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It's just something that savers and households now appreciate that times are getting uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be nationalizing another bank badly affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, including over US$41 billion (75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander informed yesterday that it was she who would buy the branches and accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to be nationalized by the British government since the beginning of this financial crisis.
