What could Zuschlag &amp; Company do in their invoice factory?
In the near future, on 8 October, hearings on the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly serious damage, and other charges have been brought against them, such as forgery and use of falsehood.
According to the prosecution, money from grants was spent for personal purposes, while benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money of the state and the municipalities, about 65 million HUF in total, went on the one hand in the caisses of the Fial Baloldal movement and on the other, in the pocket of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to receive the money from the subsidies obtained by issuing bills of fees, after which no real benefits were provided and thus, the associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books from the Józsefváros market, while they manufactured the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that would appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to his testimony, he had to locate pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices that they were going to introduce, among other things, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, and the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András ☆ri, who, according to our information, was mainly responsible for drafting the necessary files for obtaining the subsidies.
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place has restored a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
In the same way, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up on behalf of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which will later bear the name of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért, was full of faults of form and substance.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three bedrooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night there. However, the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty customers.
In the accounts, neither the name of Jobb Jövőért nor that of Hoppá appeared, according to the information given to the prosecution.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he immediately knew that they were false documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in a wrong place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that, according to the invoice, 100 people have stayed there, also did not collide, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have so much space.
In addition, the invoice also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The issuers of zealous invoices also did not find out about the travel agencies of Budapest, which were part of their choice, but only organized trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the accounting practices of the agency.
Moreover, as it appeared in the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while the services relating to travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices established on behalf of the Hotel Revfülöp at the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services do not bear a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. Furthermore, the hotel employees only issue printed invoices, while the fakes were handwritten.
The prosecution's investigation revealed that the "issuers" also made mistakes by mentioning as a service the transport of goods by road, which the invoice-issuing company could not exercise, since its profile was the investment council.
Moreover, it is also for defects of forms, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont proved false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó's sports internship, both of which deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
Nor did the counterfeiters pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., established in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at their home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Deliberately established invoices
Another category of invoice issuers is that of those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The foundation Esély Budapestért Alapítvány, at the request of the group of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, has established an invoice to the order of the foundation Együtt to Harmadik Évezrerit, for a sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was forced to issue false invoices by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, it cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the order of the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the association Atlasz Egyesület and the association Vörösfenyő Egyesület, for an amount of approximately HUF 5 million, but after which no benefits were actually provided.
No financial movement took place, either, as the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but this was avoided by the agencies in their accounts.
The following category of invoice companies is that of companies directly related to the accused.
Thus, the administrative delegate of the general manager of Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the fuel trade and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest, but where it was not found, was Ivan Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, the equipment was allegedly purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of this company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Ivan Kubatov would also have sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices to the order of Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt companies to Harmadik Évezrert Alapítvány, and that he seized their countervalue.
It was precisely at the request of Ivan Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies were functioning, which the accused explained by the fact that they did not receive work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-accused as well as editor of the acts of foundation of the companies, he made invoices to their names, to the order of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
Kubatov gave agencies, 15 invoices in total, issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecution thought that 10% of the amounts indicated on the invoices as well as VAT went into Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to establish fictitious invoices that were used in the context of Biztos Pont's grant application.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció and Szövetség Association in Modern Magyarországért applied to the public utility body of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They obtained this grant twice as much as HUF 500,000, but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To avoid this, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
Moreover, these invoices were found during the search carried out in Árpád Kemecsei's office in the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants will report on the method of making the invoices, as they had done before the prosecutor's office earlier.
What could be really interesting would be that the prime defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil over the whole story.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the smallest details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or perhaps the Socialists would have reached an agreement that, in exchange for the repayment of a large part of the fifty million HUF, Zussi would wear the hat alone.
Today, the latter is likely to be offended, as requests for his supervised residence, on the basis of a reduction in his conditions of detention, are continually falling into the ear of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and those who commit unreparable economic crimes, walk freely or at least wait at home for the end of the proceedings. He does not have this possibility.
The psychology of the auction: why are we spending more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Neurology and economics researchers at the University of New York have been able to update the neurological and economic bases of this well-known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced in this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research attempted to develop a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auction sales.
One of the groups of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (FMRI) process, researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, one essential element of which is the over-award of a third, the whole being under the brain stem, called striatum, was moving intensively when the part was lost.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the leak in front of the violent reaction of striatum.
In support of their theories, economists in this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups were over-bidding against a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the group about the actual value of the product in question, and they did so.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they would win the game, then they would receive an extra $15 in reward.
While the third group received this $15 before the auction, the members of the group also lost that money in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is, in fact, that the emphasis was on victory in one group, while the focus was on failure in the other group.
Thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the players' team "against failure" were willing to bet higher than those performed by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each one explained the phenomena found in auction sales only by the pleasure of winning and the parade at risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation." - noted Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that one hundred thousand patients carry the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles are treated because of the fact that patients often do not know that they carry the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and induced diseases differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogen genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g., contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine for C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach ailments and nausea.
Then a visible yellowness develops on the skin and on the white of the eye, the stools become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not aware of the virus, because the pathogenic gene disproportionately destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
The contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected through a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor when symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of a cancer is prevented.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from around the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does anyone who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of recent research, religious belief would function as a sort of painkiller, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers from the University of Oxford have realized an interesting experience by analyzing the level at which belief in God can influence tolerance for human pain.
As part of this strange experience, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiences, in which academicians, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
Specifically, the experiment takes place as follows: an instrument that emits sparks and diffuses electroshocks is attached to the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings in a sustained way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evokes a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, focused on its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time, they received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while looking at either the religious theme painting or the more general theme painting.
The Catholics declared that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt as "safe", as someone "take care of" and they "quietly, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious theme, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided he finds the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases, it does change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, all that remains is the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if we showed the believers a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the view of a Virgin Mary of better quality produce better results?
