What happens if someone uses my data against me, if they look at what my work is? users ask, who worry seeing Google's monopoly of information.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can arouse fear, and it is not the remorse, the fear of punishment, the desire for freedom or possibly the revolt against power that can provoke a counter-reaction among Internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that the terms sought are not only registered, but in justified cases they are passed on to a third party, and in such legal cases, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example of recent years is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian paedophiles, during which Google transmitted to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, thus allowing an identification.
Human rights-conscious Internet users were able to breathe a sigh of relief last May, when Google, arm above arm with EFF's electronic legal protection agency, proved its right to the court before the FBI. According to the ruling rendered, in the future, Google will still not be obliged by any of the constitutional points to disclose information about the FBI's secret request, of any kind.
