The smart car mimics the theft of the buzzard
What method would be better for developing technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CETEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave the strategic idea of starting Nissan engineers, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired auto-robotized control system, type BR23C, which it has equipped with bees' qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval in shape, which in reality looks very much like our secure protective shell - Kazuhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand, explained during the exhibition.
The bee's faceted eye plays a key role, as it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any system currently in place, this avoidance maneuver is carried out entirely instinctively.
"If not, the mini-auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotized car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, the acceleration and the slowing down as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy concentration, making their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only deal with a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory continuously.
We don't need memory of a gigabyte capacity, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology used for instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter the mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
