The written version of the $700 billion economic rescue plan, which aims to buy back dubious loans from banks, and to be used several times, is ready.
In the first round, half of this money will be spent.
Reuters announces that in further discussions extending until after midnight on Saturday, local East Coast time, Congressional leaders have agreed on the controversy that has existed for days and days around the $700 billion bailout plan.
"We have taken a serious step forward" - said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic President of the American House of Representatives, according to which all that remains is to put the agreements on paper.
The compromise, born from the plan, is supported by the two presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
The US Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, commented on the results of the compromise that the program will work and be effective, but other measures still need to be implemented. According to Pelosi, it is not, here, about saving Wall Street, but about turning the machinery of the economy in the other direction.
The written version of the plan was made public before the opening of the Asian markets, Sunday evening at 8 p.m., Washington local time (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m., according to the Central European local time), but did not cause a spectacular rise in the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill in the name of the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act. Then, its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday evening, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and then the White House also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"We are pleased with the progress made last night, and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, the White House spokesman.
In addition, the program diverges from the original Bush administration proposal, which stated that the $700 billion had to be spent in one go, for the redemption of dubious credits.
From now on, up to half of the 700 billion can be spent. The first 250 billion will be issued immediately after Congress passed the law, probably on Monday. This first sum will be used by the Secretary of the Treasury to buy suspicious claims from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the President's discretion.
The program will be overseen by an independent body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The expenditure of the second half of the 700 billion depends on a new Congressional decree.
Under the law, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to put in place a combined strategy: at the same time, it will be able to purchase doubtful claims, securities relating to doubtful mortgages and mortgages, as well as other types of "toxic" claims.
The department's competent individuals stated that buybacks may take place as part of an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to take part in an insurance program, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools behind the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson stated that the law provides the necessary tools to devote $700 billion to the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it is the vast buy-back of doubtful debts, their insurance, or to avoid the risk of the system leading to the collapse of one or other major financial institution.
"We will make the necessary arrangements, to be ready for law enforcement, as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the other hand, bank managers in poor postures and waiting for state aid can expect their severance payments, simply called a gold parachute overseas, to be capped by the government.
Salary ceilings are only mentioned in specific cases, and limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat offers its assistance to the company.
The cap principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys back as part of an auction, they will levy a surplus of tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly after the redemption of the doubtful debts, the government will act aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the officers is not exaggerated.
In order for the image to be complete, it must be added that the existing golden parachutes are not changed. The cap only concerns new contracts, thus motivating participation in the plan.
This is the first time in the history of the United States that legal caps will be in effect regarding the additions of the Directors General - commented the chairman of the commission in charge of the financial benefits of the Chamber of Deputies, the Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the State obtains a right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the plan, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since they can even be a winner in the case as soon as the economy and with it the banks saved will fall back on their feet.
The bill mentions that in the next five years, the President must submit to Congress a proposal that will decide how the losses will be returned to taxpayers, from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
That's not why American citizens have sent us, this does not protect taxpayers' dollars - said California Republican MP Darrell Issa.
Her Ohio Democrat colleague, Mary Kaptur, believes that they are the same people who are pressing for action, as are those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to the month of August 2007 - reports the Hungarian Central Statistical Office.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent, compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors were only slightly higher in the order of 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with a monthly increase of 2.5 per cent.
The higher prices of plastics and chemical raw materials resulted in a substantial monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This has resulted in a deflation in the oil processing (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 per cent), and a minimal increase in the wood processing (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase from 0.2 percent to 0.9 percent.
In the sectors of electricity, gas, steam and water supply, which account for a significant share of domestic industrial exploitation, prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, the most significant increase (32.4 per cent) was in the oil processing sector.
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices rose by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have taken place in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 percent to 9.1 percent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices have increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded the previous year by 18.7 per cent.
Among the domestic trade groups and by sector allocation, in August, the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was shown by the investment profit-making sectors.
In consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while in energy and materials-producing sectors for further processing there was no change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, an inflation rate of 6.8 per cent was measured, while in the profit-initiating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent.
Export prices for the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
