No opposition MPs joined the Belarusian parliament after Sunday's elections.
According to Russian observers, this is due to a country led by Alexandre Lukashenko, which provides him with prosperity and stability, while according to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), this is due to illegalities committed in the counting of votes.
The OSCE, having sent 450 observers from 43 countries, does not recognize the elections.
Although the legislative system of 110 people in this country of 10 million people has been very well opposed for decades, before yesterday's elections, the opposition uniting its forces under the name of the United Democratic Forces (ODSZ) seriously hoped that Lukashenko, renewing his term as president for the fourth time in question elections, in the wake of the 2006 amendment of the constitution, would "allow" this time the presence of a few members of the opposition in parliament.
In this way, the ODSZ gave up its original boycott.
The fact that Belarus, increasingly economically dependent on Russia, would like to improve its relations with the EU, where due to the Belarusian political order described as anti-democratic, Lukashenko and several high-ranking politicians do not receive an entry visa, was one of the opposition's expectations. Belarus had to take credit because of the declining imports of Russian natural gas, which is increasingly expensive, and thus contributed to the passage of Beltransgaz, owner of the gas pipelines crossing the country, passed into the hands of the Russians.
The fact that the OSCE, in the evaluation of the campaign, focused on positive changes rather than failures, such as the ban on one-third of opposition candidates, referred to a prior calming.
However, the OSCE press release on Monday was already challenging the campaign, during which most opposition candidates could not appear in the media, and particularly the fact that the opposition could not be present at the counting of votes.
Despite all this, the opposition still feels a tangible improvement in the political regime: political prisoners have regained freedom, and Minsk is ready for small confrontations with Moscow, still refusing to recognize South Ossetia and Abazzia separated from Georgia. However, Russia with whom Belarus forms a confederation on paper, considers the two independent territories for already a month.
"We took two steps forward, and one step back, but the most important thing is that the dialogue was initiated between Belarus and the EU" - said Alexandre Milinkevich to our newspaper.
According to the opposition candidate in the 2006 presidential elections, it is desirable that this remains so, despite the fact that "the power was afraid in this parliament that has no weight, to bring in even one opponent".
The opposition does not foresee protest actions in the light of the results, but rather attempts to send its message on the need for economic reforms to the electorate.
