Mp3 player pointed at the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to full-volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent damage to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a communiqué issued in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the recent and unexpected health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific report - we read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable music devices, for more than one hour per day and per week, risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data- continues the responsible EU- this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information publicly available.
We must also review existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"Scientists-concludes the EU executive- confirm that there are good reasons to worry, and that the European Commission will now examine with Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents, against exposure to noise from portable music and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is increased concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit these data well using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee points out that users of portable music devices, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the limits currently in force for the maximum noise level at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This concerns 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
