The elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion rescue plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms this by telling us that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more shared between its watchful East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions as well as the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to " Washington" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the Central and Southern states.
The soul, in fact, that made itself felt despotically with the vote that I spoke to you at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is just an example of the changes, the major changes that the economic earthquake is in progress or is already letting run: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
In both the United States and Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena that have existed for some time, to such an extent that, in the new climate, they become more solid and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-updating, the extraordinary revival, of the dual state-sovereign category, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with abroad, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families living in one country, in one State.
This immediately creates a political problem for whom it governs: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears to be economically global, but politically, it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalisation seems really out of the question, or it has little to say: the obvious proof is given to us by the European Union, which, as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, is unable to decide any common policy line.
And so, it is from the government of each state that all expect interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a credit ailment: when one goes through a difficult period, there are only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no market or international organization will ever be able to dispose of in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the state-nation crisis is moreover in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite linked to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of the ever more sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized in one stroke, that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with things rather little material like water, harvests, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but that are absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly possesses more cards than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the misfortune of living in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, provides for a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably called Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadow zone.
And in addition, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discredit, suffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of West countries.
This further increases the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of the majorities.
In short, The demand for leadership, feeds underground, a powerful and ramified movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral "revolts" or, in the changes of collective moods of the latter all the time, from the conservative ascension in Austria Bavaria, to the fall of the workers in Great Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not arrive by chance).
It is felt that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, would say someone, have more and more difficulty, which does not date from today, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis strengthens, increases and acts potentially in a way that is far too much.
