The superglue to walk on the walls.
Defeating the laws of gravity through super glue and, in the future, walking on walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centres, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring barely 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers managed to keep a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
STUDY- The American journal Science has published the discoveries of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular carbon structure, called nano carbon tubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged as a spaghetti pile." Explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Atlanta Georgia Institute of Technology.
Scientists have inspired the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that allow to assure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it "removes easily from the wall," explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's Faculty of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive," says Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since nano carbon tubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could include aerospace engineering.
For now, no superheroes.
