Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, mainly consumed in the summer because they are desaltering and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital medicines, alter the absorption that amplifies or diminishes, depending on the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, associated with the ingestion of certain medicines; during the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he launched a new alarm: just a glass of grapefruit juice, orange and apples, to reduce the absorption of certain vital medicines, cancelling their beneficial effects and endangering the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized as being responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-stamine and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
