Student victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for one room.
The student rental market knows no crisis
According to Sunia's latest investigation, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that the families of origin must support- explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the strong demand from the students has distorted the market so much that a process of general increase has begun for the residents themselves.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free, unregistered, rent-free, sub-hire contracts.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the tax review are needed to calm prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza zone, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from 650 euros minimum (Black Band zone), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate zone, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria zone)
In Florence, an average bed costs 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a double bed, and 370 to 500 euros for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are requested for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
A slightly lower value (550 euros for a single one) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
One can save only if one moves away in the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 euros for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, we spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the zones Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, it is necessary to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the city economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, where rents are often taken by extra-Community students, have a subsequent anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities elevate the historic halls.
The historic cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of marginalisation of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of the large multi-salles, and the death of consumption of mono-salles in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and incontestable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and loaded with memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of a path and so many emotions" observes the director of Nuovo cinéma Paradiso, a film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar and the Grand Prix de la jure de Cannes, and which recounts the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way of living the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of traditional type have closed, and it is the halls of the main cities that have paid the most for them: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, the Emilia Romaine is in the lead with 82 single cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," notes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a firm room in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of credit in favour of traders: the historical debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros a year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about these closures, decided to solve the situation through the signing of a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote the cinemas mono rooms of the historical centres and in the periphery.
Among the regulations provided for, there are tax facilitation measures for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted area, and will have special rates for parking and certain parking spaces.
"It is an initiative that I like" observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
It is clear, however, that in order to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, because today's public is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much shared emotions, I turn to the other side not to see the signs blackened by dust.
