When the energy comes out of the waves, now the big ones start.
This is a disproportionate deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and now the world's largest energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colossal people like Chevron have laid their eyes, and now they're trying to get their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has now been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When the price of oil dropped by 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity demand could be covered by sea swell operating systems.
This quantity would be twice as high as that produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides..
Colossians on attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it looked like a real revolutionary step.
Two years away from this, more and more candidates among these companies, which have always been dedicated to traditional energy, rely on marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies," said the spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil colossus, the Wall Street Journal, "and it is assessing the possibilities of cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially if we consider that, precisely in Alaska, the US continues to extract oil, and President Bush has recently put in place a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, which are on the way to energy from the sea, and the sums invested to date, although their details are not known, indicate, according to observers, an increasing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in its early stages, apart from the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce large-scale energy, however, technologies with a higher environmental impact need to be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a buoy system connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which moves the sludge upwards and downwards, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine that, in turn, feeds a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through underwater cables.
For the time being, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending a single federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the contrary, already produces energy for a mall and a parking lot using six submarine turbines from the East River in New York.
The movement of the water during the tides, turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotating movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant has announced to have a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for the Research of Electrical Energy, deserves right now, the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable of wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coast, invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and plans investments up to 35 million in 2009.
